 then, using wet hands, flatten to form large patties (Ø 12-13 cm). Transfer to prepared tray, cover with cling film and chill in fridge for 30 minutes. Towards the end of this time, preheat oven to 190°C."},{"isHeader":true,"content":"Sweet Potato Wedges"},{"content":"Spray a large baking tray with oil. Arrange sweet potato wedges on prepared tray, sprinkle with garlic powder, paprika, salt and pepper then toss to coat. Bake for 40 minutes (190°C). With 15 minutes remaining, place chilled patties in oven too and bake for 12-15 minutes (190°C) until cooked, flipping halfway through."},{"isHeader":true,"content":"Assembly"},{"content":"Divide lettuce and tomatoes between buns then place a cooked beef patty on each. Top with cheese, onion and ketchup. Serve with sweet potato wedges."}],"hintsAndTricks":["Think you can't eat burgers and chips on a diet? Think again! These clever beef burgers are made with low-fat mince, and we've baked them instead of frying them. Topped with a slice of reduced fat cheese and served with sweet potato wedges, all that's needed is a squirt of tomato ketchup to finish!","To reduce the calories even more, try serving these burgers with baked carrot or butternut squash chips instead of sweet potato wedges."],"basicInfo":["easy","30m","1h 40m","4 portions"]}